        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-09T23:47:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This may also have concrete side effects, right: like allowing invocations of the trigger_wait operation registered by trigger_wait, to return?  That\u0027s what I meant by the tension between whether \"signaled\" is concrete or abstract.  I think of this letting the \"trigger_wait\" operations return as \"signaling\".  Though maybe you can just finesse it here, with some statement here about allowing trigger_wait operations to return.\n\n(It\u0027s a little weird that you have to register the trigger_wait, but the function you register is supposed to interact with this spec in this way.  Maybe I\u0027m getting something wrong here?  I need to find the function you register via register_trigger_wait...)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 130,
